6. Why your “same humans” intuition is strong

Because at long scales, a lot of civilization is not about new minds appearing.
It is about the same minds encountering:
	•	new surplus
	•	new bottlenecks
	•	new symbols
	•	new coordination tools
	•	new punishments
	•	new freedoms

Humans are ancient.
Contexts are what mutate faster.

So yes: one fruitful working assumption is that much of history can be modeled as:

stable human substrate + changing wrappers + path dependence

That is a powerful simplification.

⸻

7. Best Version of Your Seed Idea

The best formulation is:

Use the present not as a copy-source, but as a distribution-source.

Not:
	•	“this person becomes a Roman”

But:
	•	“from present human variation, derive bounded synthetic seeds that span the likely ancient behavioral manifold”

That is elegant, safer, and probably more scientifically useful.

